<div style="text-align:center"><div style="width:8.5in;text-align:left;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto">

<table style="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;border:0;width:100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
<tr style="page-break-inside:avoid">
<td style="width:11%;vertical-align:top" align="left"><span style="font-weight:bold">Item&#160;8.01</span></td>
<td align="left" style="vertical-align:top"> <p style=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman;font-weight:bold;text-align:left">Other Events </p></td></tr></table> <p style="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">On June&#160;14, 2021, Terns Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (the &#8220;Company&#8221; or &#8220;Terns&#8221;) announced positive <span style="white-space:nowrap">top-line</span> data from its Phase 2a LIFT trial of <span style="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</span> in NASH patients. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">On June&#160;14, 2021, the Company issued a press release and provided a corporate presentation relating to its topline results from its Phase 2a LIFT trial of <span style="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</span> in NASH patients. A copy of the press release and the presentation are filed as Exhibits 99.1 and 99.2 to this Current Report on Form <span style="white-space:nowrap">8-K</span> and are incorporated herein by reference. </p> <p style="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The information contained in the press release and the presentation is summary information that is intended to be considered in the context of the more complete information included in the Company&#8217;s filings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#8220;SEC&#8221;) and other public announcements that the Company has made and may make from time to time. The Company undertakes no duty or obligation to update or revise the information contained in this report, although it may do so from time to time as its management believes is appropriate. Any such update may be made through the filing of other reports or documents with the SEC. </p> <p style="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&#160;</p>

<DESCRIPTION>EX-99.1
<TEXT>
<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>EX-99.1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 <BODY BGCOLOR="WHITE">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="right"><B>Exhibit 99.1 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>Terns Reports Positive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Top-line</FONT> Results from Phase 2a LIFT Study of FXR Agonist <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> in Patients with NASH </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><I>First FXR agonist trial to demonstrate no discontinuations due to
AEs, including pruritus, and both a differentiated pruritus and lipid profile in patients with NASH </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><I>First <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">12-week</FONT> controlled trial in patients with NASH to show significant improvements in corrected T1 (cT1), an imaging marker of liver inflammation and fibrosis linked to clinical outcomes </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><I>Terns plans to initiate first NASH trial of an FXR agonist <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(TERN-101)</FONT> in combination with</I> <I>a
THR-</I>&szlig;<I> agonist <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(TERN-501)</FONT> in 1H22</I> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><I>Company to host conference call and webcast
at 8:30 a.m. ET today </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">FOSTER CITY, Calif., June&nbsp;14, 2021 &#150; Terns Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (&#147;Terns&#148; or the &#147;Company&#148;)
(Nasdaq: TERN), a clinical-stage biopharmaceutical company developing a portfolio of small-molecule single-agent and combination therapy candidates for the treatment of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-alcoholic</FONT> steatohepatitis (NASH) and
other chronic liver diseases, today reported positive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">top-line</FONT> results from the Phase 2a LIFT clinical trial of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101,</FONT> a liver-distributed farnesoid X receptor (FXR)
agonist for the treatment of patients with NASH. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The LIFT study is a multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, parallel-group, Phase 2a
clinical trial to evaluate the safety, tolerability, efficacy, and pharmacokinetics of orally-administered <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> tablets at doses of 5 mg, 10 mg and 15 mg in 100 adult patients with presumed <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-cirrhotic</FONT> <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-alcoholic</FONT> steatohepatitis (NASH). The primary objective of the clinical trial was to evaluate the safety and tolerability of
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> over 12 weeks of treatment plus a four-week post-treatment <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">follow-up</FONT> period. Secondary endpoints included percent change from baseline in ALT levels and plasma
pharmacokinetics of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101.</FONT> Exploratory efficacy endpoints included changes in liver fibro-inflammation measured by MRI corrected T1 (cT1), liver fat content by MRI proton density fat fraction <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(MRI-PDFF),</FONT> pharmacodynamic parameters, and serum NASH biomarkers. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In the LIFT trial,
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> was generally well tolerated with a similar incidence of adverse events (AEs) across treatment groups. All treatment-related adverse events were mild/moderate with no apparent dose relationship. There
were no treatment-related serious adverse events, and no patient discontinued <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> due to any adverse event including pruritus. The most frequent treatment-emergent adverse events included pruritus,
headache, constipation, diarrhea, decreased appetite and dizziness. Pruritus was reported in four patients (16%) in the 5 mg <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> arm, three patients (11.5%) in the 10 mg
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> arm, four patients (17.4%) in the 15 mg <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> arm and no patients in the placebo group. Three pruritus cases were Grade 2 (widespread and intermittent); the
rest were Grade 1 (mild or localized). Notably, there were no Grade 3 (widespread and constant) pruritus events and no discontinuations due to pruritus. Most pruritus cases resolved during continued <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT>
treatment. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">No change in LDL cholesterol was observed in patients in the 5 mg and 10 mg
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> arms as compared to placebo (Week 12 mean change: 4.8% for placebo, 6.7% for 5 mg <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101,</FONT> 3.2% for 10 mg <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101,</FONT> not
significant). Statistically significant LDL changes were observed only in the 15 mg arm (Week 12 mean change: 15.9%, p&lt;0.05). Significant decreases in HDL cholesterol were observed in all <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> dose
groups at Week 4 and Week 8 but returned toward baseline in the 5 mg and 10 mg dose groups without differences from placebo at Week 12. Decreases in HDL were significantly different from placebo for the 15 mg group at all observed timepoints through
Week 12. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Multiple efficacy biomarkers of NASH, including corrected T1 (cT1), <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">MRI-PDFF</FONT> and ALT, were evaluated in
the LIFT Study: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Mean changes in cT1 at Week 12 were <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-0.8</FONT> msec for placebo, <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-38.0</FONT> msec (p=0.033) for the 5 mg arm, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-57.7</FONT> msec (p=0.002) for the 10 mg arm, and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-74.0</FONT> msec (p&lt;0.001) for the 15 mg arm.
Improvements of at least 80 msec in cT1 were observed in a significant proportion of patients in the 5 mg and 10 mg groups at Week 12 (as compared to placebo). Significant decreases in cT1 were also observed at Week 6 for all dose groups. cT1 is a
magnetic resonance-based imaging test measuring free-water content in liver tissue, which has shown a strong correlation with inflammation and fibrosis histology and clinical outcomes in patients with liver disease. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Mean relative changes in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">MRI-PDFF</FONT> were
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-8.4%</FONT> (placebo), <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-15.1%</FONT> (5 mg), <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-19.7%</FONT> (10 mg), and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-12.9%</FONT> (15 mg) at Week 12. Mean
relative changes in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">MRI-PDFF</FONT> were significant at Week 6 for the 10 mg and 15 mg dose groups compared to placebo, although these changes were not statistically significant at Week 12. <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">MRI-PDFF</FONT> is an imaging marker that measures liver fat content. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Mean percent changes in ALT at Week 12 were <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-5.3%</FONT> (placebo), <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-2.6%</FONT> (5 mg), <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-18%</FONT> (10 mg), and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-13.2%</FONT> (15 mg). </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">No discernable trends were observed in initial analyses of the enhanced liver fibrosis (ELF) score, <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">CK-18</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-C3.</FONT> </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#147;NASH is a complex multifaceted
condition, making it difficult to use just one target to treat the disease. The LIFT data are exciting because we see improvement in key <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-invasive</FONT> tests associated with disease severity along with an
attractive safety profile with no discontinuations due to side effects,&#148; said Rohit Loomba, MD,&nbsp;MHSc, director of the UC San Diego NAFLD Research Center and director of Hepatology at UC San Diego School of Medicine. &#147;The results add
to the growing body of evidence showing the promise of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> as a multi-modal therapy to treat the multiple facets of this disease.&#148; </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">*</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman; " ALIGN="left">p&lt;0.05, **p&lt;0.01, ***p&lt;0.001 versus placebo </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">+</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman; " ALIGN="left">cT1 was conducted only at available sites (n=22, 24, 20 and 18 for placebo, 5 mg, 10 mg and 15 mg groups,
respectively). </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#147;We are encouraged by the positive effects of well tolerated doses of
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> on cT1 relaxation time, a biomarker correlated with improved clinical outcomes. LIFT is the first controlled NASH trial to show significant cT1 improvement as early as Week 6. <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> has the potential to be an effective component of a NASH treatment regimen. We look forward to advancing this program in our planned combination therapy trial,&#148; said Erin Quirk, MD, president, chief
medical officer and head of research and development at Terns. &#147;I would like to thank all those who have helped us rapidly advance the LIFT Study, including our outstanding team of investigators and clinical sites, the members of the Terns
team, and the patients who participated in the study.&#148;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Terns plans to submit data from the LIFT Study to an upcoming scientific conference. Based on
these positive results, Terns continues to plan a combination trial of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> together with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-501,</FONT> the Company&#146;s thyroid hormone receptor beta agonist <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(THR-&szlig;)</FONT> also in development for the treatment of NASH. The multiple ascending dose portion of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-501</FONT> Phase 1 trial started in June 2021, and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">top-line</FONT> data from the trial is expected in the second half of 2021. The combination trial of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-501</FONT> is expected to
start in the first half of 2022. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Investor Conference Call </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Terns will host an update call for investors today, June&nbsp;14, 2021, beginning at 8:30 a.m. ET. The webcast of the conference call will be made available at
<U>https://edge.media-server.com/mmc/p/2gsxxmta</U>. To access the call via <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">dial-in,</FONT> please dial <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">1-833-665-0612</FONT></FONT> (U.S./Canada
toll-free) or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">1-929-517-0403</FONT></FONT></FONT> (international) using the conference code 7587739. A replay of the call will also be available on
the investor page of the Terns website for 30 days. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>About <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101</FONT> is a liver-distributed, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-bile</FONT> acid FXR agonist that has
demonstrated a differentiated tolerability profile and improved target engagement, likely due to its sustained FXR activation in the liver but only transient FXR activation in the intestine. FXR is a nuclear receptor primarily expressed in the
liver, intestine and kidneys. FXR regulates hepatic expression of various genes involved in lipid metabolism, inflammation and fibrosis. Clinical studies of other FXR agonists have demonstrated significant histological NASH improvements but have
also resulted in pruritus, adverse lipid changes and discontinuations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>About Terns Pharmaceuticals </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Terns Pharmaceuticals, Inc. is a clinical-stage biopharmaceutical company developing a portfolio of small-molecule single-agent and combination therapy
candidates for the treatment of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-alcoholic</FONT> steatohepatitis, or NASH, and other chronic liver diseases. Terns&#146; <U>programs</U> are based on clinically validated and complementary mechanisms of action to
address the multiple hepatic disease processes of NASH in order to drive meaningful clinical benefits for patients. For more information, please visit <U>www.ternspharma.com</U>. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Cautionary Note Regarding Forward-Looking Statements</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">This

the Phase 2a LIFT Study of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">TERN-101;</FONT> expectations of timing and potential results of the Company&#146;s clinical trials; the Company&#146;s clinical development plans and activities, including the development

and fibrosis linked to clinical outcomes1 - Also observed improvements in PDFF and liver enzymes First NASH trial of an FXR agonist (TERN-101) in combination with a THR-p agonist (TERN-501) planned for 1H22 initiation - TERN-501 Phase 1 MAD portion
started in June 2021 with data expected in 2H 2021 AE = adverse event. SAE = severe adverse event. FXR = farnesoid X receptor. NASH = nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. THR=thyroid hormone receptor 1. Liver International. 2020;40:3071-3082 </FONT></P>

 </P> <P STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">Most Frequent Treatment-Emergent Adverse Events All treatment-related AEs were mild/moderate with no apparent dose-relationship
Pruritus: no Grade 3; no discontinuations; most resolved with continued dosing </FONT></P>
</DIV></Center>

 </P> <P STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">3LIFT 3 Important Firsts for NASH Treatment First FXR agonist trial to demonstrate no discontinuations due to AEs, including pruritus
TERN-101 was generally well-tolerated with similar incidence of AEs across treatment groups No treatment-related SAEs First 12-week controlled trial in NASH to show significant improvements in cT1 cT1 is an imaging marker of liver inflammation and
fibrosis linked to clinical outcomes1 Also observed improvements in PDFF and liver enzymes First NASH trial of an FXR agonist (TERN-101) in combination with a THR-p agonist (TERN-501) planned for 1H22 initiation - TERN-501 Phase 1 MAD portion
started in June 2021 with data expected in 2H 2021 AE = adverse event. SAE = severe adverse event. FXR = farnesoid X receptor. NASH = nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. THR=thyroid hormone receptor 1. Liver International. 2020;40:3071-3082 </FONT></P>

 </P> <P STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:0.5pt"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">TERN-501: Differentiated THR-0 AgonistTHR-p regulates key aspects of energy metabolism (e.g., fatty acid &amp; lipid synthesis, liver
fat removal through fatty acid oxidation) &#149; TERN-501 is a selective Thyroid Hormone Receptor beta (THR-p) agonist with enhanced metabolic stability and liver distribution Other THR-p agonists face limitations with off- target effects or
unpredictable PK due to CYP metabolism TERN-501 was screened for greater selectivity and enhanced metabolic and PK stability - Expected low clinical dose - Attractive for monotherapy or combination therapy &#149; Phase 1 SAD/MAD </FONT></P>
</DIV></Center>

var Show={};Show.LastAR=null,Show.showAR=function(a,r,w){if(Show.LastAR)Show.hideAR();var e=a;while(e&&e.nodeName!='TABLE')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e||e.nodeName!='TABLE'){var ref=((window)?w.document:document).getElementById(r);if(ref){e=ref.cloneNode(!0);
e.removeAttribute('id');a.parentNode.appendChild(e)}}
if(e)e.style.display='block';Show.LastAR=e};Show.hideAR=function(){Show.LastAR.style.display='none'};Show.toggleNext=function(a){var e=a;while(e.nodeName!='DIV')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e.style){}else if(!e.style.display){}else{var d,p_;if(e.style.display=='none'){d='block';p='-'}else{d='none';p='+'}
e.style.display=d;if(a.textContent){a.textContent=p+a.textContent.substring(1)}else{a.innerText=p+a.innerText.substring(1)}}}

/* Updated 2009-11-04 */

/* DefRef Styles */
..report table.authRefData{
	background-color: #def;
	border: 2px solid #2F4497;
	font-size: 1em;
	position: absolute;
}

..report table.authRefData a {
	display: block;
	font-weight: bold;
}

	margin-top: 0px;
}

	background-color: #2F4497;
	padding: 1px 3px 0px 0px;
	text-align: right;
}

	background-color: #2F4497;
}

	height: 150px;
	overflow: auto;
	width: 400px;
}

	font-size: 1em;
}

	color: black;
	text-decoration: none;
}

}

/* Header rows... */
..report tr.rh {
	background-color: #acf;
	color: black;
	font-weight: bold;
}

/* Calendars... */
..report .rc {
	background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

/* Even rows... */
..report .re, .report .reu {
	background-color: #def;
}

..report .reu td {
	border-bottom: 1px solid black;
}

/* Odd rows... */
..report .ro, .report .rou {
	background-color: white;
}

..report .rou td {
	border-bottom: 1px solid black;
}

..report .rou table td, .report .reu table td {
	border-bottom: 0px solid black;
}

/* styles for footnote marker */
..report .fn {
	white-space: nowrap;
}

/* styles for numeric types */
..report .num, .report .nump {
	text-align: right;
	white-space: nowrap;
}

..report .nump {
	padding-left: 2em;
}

..report .nump {
	padding: 0px 0.4em 0px 2em;
}

/* styles for text types */
..report .text {
	text-align: left;
	white-space: normal;
}

..report .text .big {
	margin-bottom: 1em;
	width: 17em;
}

..report .text .more {
	display: none;
}

..report .text .note {
	font-style: italic;
	font-weight: bold;
}

..report .text .small {
	width: 10em;
}

..report sup {
	font-style: italic;
}

..report .outerFootnotes {
	font-size: 1em;
}
